      <section class="dbc-section dbc-top-section dbc-element dbc-element-d5f0d8a dbc-section-boxed dbc-section-height-default dbc-section-height-default" data-id="d5f0d8a" data-element_type="section">
        <div class="dbc-container dbc-column-gap-default">
          <div class="dbc-column dbc-col-100 dbc-top-column dbc-element dbc-element-0c03a27" data-id="0c03a27" data-element_type="column">
            <div class="dbc-widget-wrap dbc-element-populated">
              <div class="dbc-element dbc-element-b14c1f8 dbc-widget dbc-widget-text-editor" data-id="b14c1f8" data-element_type="widget" data-widget_type="text-editor.default">
                <div class="dbc-widget-container">
                  <p><span style="color: #000000;">Mesenchymal stem cells (MSCs) treat Myasthenia Gravis (MG) by modulating the immune system, reducing inflammation, and promoting tissue repair. MSCs have the potential to suppress the immune response and decrease the number of inflammatory cells causing damage to muscle tissue in patients with MG. They also promote tissue repair and regeneration, which can help to improve muscle function and reduce or eliminate symptoms associated with MG.</span></p>
                  <p><span style="color: #000000;">Studies have demonstrated the effectiveness of MSCs in treating MG. In human clinical trials, MSC therapy has shown positive outcomes, including improved muscle strength, reduced disease activity, and decreased or elimination of need for immunosuppressive drug therapy.</span></p>
                  <p><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Fix the Faulty Immune System:</span> The 300 million stem cell IV will send stem cells throughout the body. They will first go to the heart then to the lungs. At the lungs about 70% will get stuck. This is because of micro-capillaries and small blood vessels there. These MSCs are not wasted though. They will interact with passing immune cells such as T cells, B cells, dendric cell, NK cells and more. If they detect that any of these immune cells are not functioning properly then they will send out cytokines and other signals to essentially reprogram the immune cells. It is like uploading new software to an old computer. It will get rid of the bad programming and update it with instructions to protect the neuromuscular system instead of attacking it. The best part is that these results appear to last long term. We use such a high dose of stem cells in hopes that this is a one time treatment and your muscular function goes back to normal.</span></p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>
