      <section class="dbc-section dbc-top-section dbc-element dbc-element-4c30a87 dbc-section-boxed dbc-section-height-default dbc-section-height-default" data-id="4c30a87" data-element_type="section">
        <div class="dbc-container dbc-column-gap-default">
          <div class="dbc-column dbc-col-100 dbc-top-column dbc-element dbc-element-95faf2d" data-id="95faf2d" data-element_type="column">
            <div class="dbc-widget-wrap dbc-element-populated">
              <div class="dbc-element dbc-element-da38a9e dbc-widget dbc-widget-text-editor" data-id="da38a9e" data-element_type="widget" data-widget_type="text-editor.default">
                <div class="dbc-widget-container">
                  <p><span style="color: #000000;">Mesenchymal stem cells (MSCs) can work with several types of trophic factors to treat Myasthenia Gravis (MG). Trophic factors are proteins that support cell growth, development, and function.</span></p>
                  <p><span style="color: #000000;">One of the main trophic factors that MSCs can work with is nerve growth factor (NGF), which promotes the growth and differentiation of nerve cells. NGF can help to improve the function of nerve cells that have been damaged by the autoimmune response in MG, improving muscle function.</span></p>
                  <p><span style="color: #000000;">Another trophic factor that MSCs can work with is brain-derived neurotrophic factor (BDNF), which is involved in the growth and differentiation of nerve cells and can also promote the survival of existing nerve cells.</span></p>
                  <p><span style="color: #000000;">MSCs can also work with fibroblast growth factor (FGF), which is involved in the regeneration of injured tissues, including muscle tissue. FGF can help to promote angiogenesis and stimulate the growth and differentiation of stem cells involved in tissue repair.</span></p>
                  <p><span style="color: #000000;">Moreover, MSCs can work with vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF), a trophic factor that promotes the growth of blood vessels and enhances blood flow to injured tissues. VEGF helps to provide essential oxygen and nutrients to muscle cells, facilitating repair and regeneration.</span></p>
                  <p><span style="color: #000000;">Overall, MSCs can work with several trophic factors to promote tissue repair and regeneration and improve muscle function in MG patients.</span></p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>
