      <section class="dbc-section dbc-top-section dbc-element dbc-element-e6dd80a dbc-section-boxed dbc-section-height-default dbc-section-height-default" data-id="e6dd80a" data-element_type="section">
        <div class="dbc-container dbc-column-gap-default">
          <div class="dbc-column dbc-col-100 dbc-top-column dbc-element dbc-element-5012151" data-id="5012151" data-element_type="column">
            <div class="dbc-widget-wrap dbc-element-populated">
              <div class="dbc-element dbc-element-23dc6c5 dbc-widget dbc-widget-text-editor" data-id="23dc6c5" data-element_type="widget" data-widget_type="text-editor.default">
                <div class="dbc-widget-container">
                  <p><span style="color: #000000;">Mesenchymal stem cells (MSCs) possess several anti-inflammatory properties that may potentially benefit individuals with an enlarged prostate, also known as benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH). These properties include:</span></p><ol><li><p><span style="color: #000000;"><strong>Modulation of cytokine secretion:</strong> MSCs have the ability to regulate the secretion of pro-inflammatory cytokines, such as tumor necrosis factor-alpha (TNF-α), interleukin-1 beta (IL-1β), and interleukin-6 (IL-6). By reducing the production of these inflammatory molecules, MSCs can help mitigate inflammation and its associated effects on the prostate.</span></p></li><li><p><span style="color: #000000;"><strong>Induction of anti-inflammatory cytokines:</strong> MSCs release anti-inflammatory cytokines, such as interleukin-10 (IL-10) and transforming growth factor-beta (TGF-β). These cytokines help counteract the pro-inflammatory response, dampening inflammation in the prostate and promoting healing.</span></p></li><li><p><span style="color: #000000;"><strong>Inhibition of immune cell activity:</strong> MSCs can suppress the activation and function of immune cells involved in the inflammatory response, such as T cells, B cells, and macrophages. This immunomodulatory effect helps reduce the immune-mediated inflammation associated with BPH.</span></p></li><li><p><span style="color: #000000;"><strong>Recruitment of regulatory immune cells:</strong> MSCs can recruit and promote the expansion of regulatory T cells (Tregs) and M2 macrophages. These immune cells have anti-inflammatory properties and can help control excessive inflammation in the prostate.</span></p></li><li><p><span style="color: #000000;"><strong>Reduction of oxidative stress:</strong> MSCs have antioxidative properties, meaning they can counteract oxidative stress induced by reactive oxygen species (ROS). Oxidative stress is a contributing factor in inflammation, and MSCs can help alleviate this stress in the prostate tissue.</span></p></li></ol><p><span style="color: #000000;">It is important to note that the specific mechanisms by which MSCs exert their anti-inflammatory effects in BPH are still being investigated, and further research is needed to fully understand their role in reducing inflammation in the prostate. We have found that our protocol of 50 million MSCs injected around the prostate via ultrasound guidance is working very well.</span></p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>
